            it is wrong that the ordered pair of m \NATplus \NATone and the value of f under z is an element of \SETsingleton{ the ordered pair of n \NATplus \NATone and y }
            the ordered pair of m \NATplus \NATone and the value of f under z is an element of H
          Qed.
          SetBytes prover "vampire"          H is an element of \Phi
          SetBytes prover "eprover"          for all v0, (if v0 is an element of \SETintersectover \Phi then v0 is an element of H)
          the ordered pair of n \NATplus \NATone and y is an element of H
          falsity holds
        Qed.
        it is wrong that (it is wrong that x is equal to the value of f under b or it is wrong that y is equal to the value of f under b)
        x is equal to the value of f under b and the value of f under b is equal to y
      Qed.
      n \NATplus \NATone is an element of \Theta
    Qed.
    for all v0, (if v0 is an element of \Nat then v0 is an element of \Theta)
  Qed.
  \varphi is a map and (the domain of \varphi is equal to \Nat) and for all v0, (if v0 is an object then (if v0 is an element of the domain of \varphi then for some v1, (v1 is an element of A and the ordered pair of v0 and v1 is an element of \SETintersectover \Phi and (the value of \varphi under v0 is equal to v1))))
  \varphi is a map from \Nat to A and the value of \varphi under \NATzero is equal to a
  for all v0, (if v0 is an element of \Nat then the value of \varphi under v0 \NATplus \NATone is equal to the value of f under the value of \varphi under v0)
  Proof:
    n is an element of \Nat
    x is an element of A and the value of \varphi under n is equal to x
    the ordered pair of n and x is an element of \SETintersectover \Phi
    the ordered pair of n \NATplus \NATone and the value of f under the value of \varphi under n is equal to the ordered pair of n \NATplus \NATone and the value of f under x and the ordered pair of n \NATplus \NATone and the value of f under x is an element of \SETintersectover \Phi
    the value of \varphi under n \NATplus \NATone is equal to the value of f under the value of \varphi under n
  Qed.
Qed.

Theorem (Dedekind_Recursion_Uniqueness):
  for all v0, (for all v1, (for all v2, (if v0 is a set and v1 is an element of v0 and v2 is a map from v0 to v0 then for all v3, (for all v4, (if v3 is a map from \Nat to v0 and v4 is a map from \Nat to v0 then (if v3 is recursively defined by v1 and v2 and v4 is recursively defined by v1 and v2 then v3 is equal to v4))))))
Proof:
  \Phi is a class and (if \Nat is a set then \Phi is a set) and for all v0, (v0 is an element of \Phi iff (v0 is an element of \Nat and v0 is an object and the value of \varphi under v0 is equal to the value of \varphi' under v0))
  \NATzero is an element of \Phi
  Proof:
    the value of \varphi under \NATzero is equal to a and a is equal to the value of \varphi' under \NATzero
  Qed.
  for all v0, (if v0 is an element of \Phi then v0 \NATplus \NATone is an element of \Phi)
  Proof:
    n is an element of \Phi
    the value of \varphi under n is equal to the value of \varphi' under n
    the value of \varphi under n \NATplus \NATone is equal to the value of f under the value of \varphi under n and the value of f under the value of \varphi under n is equal to the value of f under the value of \varphi' under n and the value of f under the value of \varphi' under n is equal to the value of \varphi' under n \NATplus \NATone
  Qed.
  for all v0, (if v0 is a natural number then v0 is an element of \Phi)
  for all v0, (if v0 is an element of \Nat then the value of \varphi under v0 is equal to the value of \varphi' under v0)
Qed.

